Listeria monocytogenes meningitis in the elderly: epidemiological, clinical and 
therapeutic findings.

Pagliano P(1), Ascione T(1), Boccia G(2), De Caro F(2), Esposito S(3).

Author information:
(1)AORN dei Colli, D. Cotugno Hospital, Department of Infectious Diseases, 
Naples, Italy.
(2)Institute of Hygiene, University of Salerno, Italy.
(3)Department of Infectious Diseases, University of Salerno, Italy.

Listeria monocytogenes is a Gram-positive bacillus and facultative intracellular 
bacterium whose transmission occurs mainly through the consumption of 
contaminated food, L. monocytogenes invades the host cells using various protein 
and can escape to the human T-cell immune system by cell-to-cell spreading. If 
the infection is not controlled at the stage in which the bacterium is in the 
liver, for instance, due to a severe immunodepression, a secondary bacteraemia 
can be developed and L. monocytogenes reaches the preferred sites transgressing 
the blood-brain barrier or the placental barrier. Individuals with T-cell 
dysfunction, such as pregnant women, the elderly, and those receiving 
